				<name type="primary" sortindex="1" value="どんでん (Donden)" />
			
						                           
						               													<description>&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#169;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#147;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#167;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#147; (Donden) is a Japanese abstract game for two players, similar to Reversi. The game has three wooden boards with 4x4 grids, and 48 chips marked on one side.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Donden was created through collaboration, born out of a project to see if something could be done using thinned wood from Sagamihara City. The game is packaged in a wrapped sleeve, made of Japanese paper. The chips are stored in the back side of the boards.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The three boards are arranged in a line. The players place two chips each from their supply in the centre, one player using the marked side.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Taking turns, a player either places a chip on the board, looking to attack as in Reversi, by flipping opponent's chips. Or a player may discard a chip and move one of the three boards around (a disturbance), thus causing an attack.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;By taking an end board, for example, the player can place it at right angles, making an L-shape. This puts one of their pieces outside their opponent's, causing an attack.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game ends when one player runs out of chips. The other player gets a final turn. Then the players get a point for each chip they have on the board, plus a point for each chip left in hand (not discards). The player with the most points wins.&amp;#10;user summary&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
